# React Component Design

You must strictly enforce these React component design standards during the implementation phase. Code that violates these rules must fail the refactoring step.

## 1. Single Responsibility
- Each component should do one thing — data fetching, transformation, and rendering in the same component must be split.
- Extract reusable UI into smaller components when duplication appears across two or more places.

## 2. Component Structure
- Order: hooks at the top, derived values, handlers, then JSX.
- Co-locate component-specific styles, types, and helpers close to the component.

## 3. Props
- Pass only the props a component needs — avoid passing large objects when only a subset is used.
- Destructure props at the function signature.
- Avoid prop drilling beyond two layers — use Context, lifting state, or restructuring.
- A component with more than 5-6 props is likely doing too much.

```jsx
<UserCard user={user} /> // Bad — passes entire object
<UserCard name={user.name} avatarUrl={user.avatarUrl} /> // Good
```

## 4. State Management
- Keep state as close as possible to where it is used.
- Use local state for UI-specific concerns (open/closed, loading, error).
- Never mutate state directly — always use immutable update patterns.
- Use functional state updates when next state depends on previous value.

```jsx
setCount(count + 1); // Bad
setCount(prev => prev + 1); // Good — safe with concurrent rendering
```

- Derive values from existing state instead of storing them separately.
- Use `useReducer` when multiple values always change together.
- Use global state (Context, Redux, Zustand) only for data genuinely shared across multiple features or pages.

## 5. Derived Data
- Compute derived values during render — never store them in `useState`.

```jsx
const [fullName, setFullName] = useState(`${firstName} ${lastName}`); // Bad — derived state
const fullName = `${firstName} ${lastName}`; // Good — computed during render
```

## 6. Business Logic & Custom Hooks
- Extract complex logic, data fetching, and side effect orchestration into custom hooks.
- Custom hooks should be focused — one hook per logical concern.
- Utility functions that don't need React state belong in plain functions, not hooks.

## 7. Side Effects
- Never use `useEffect` to derive values that can be computed directly.
- Always declare accurate dependency arrays.
- Always return a cleanup function from effects that set up subscriptions, timers, or listeners.
- Never define an `async` function directly as the `useEffect` callback — `useEffect` does not handle the returned Promise.

```jsx
useEffect(async () => { // Bad — returned Promise is ignored
  const user = await fetchUser(id);
  setUser(user);
}, [id]);

useEffect(() => { // Good
  const loadUser = async () => { const user = await fetchUser(id); setUser(user); };
  loadUser();
}, [id]);
```

## 8. Controlled vs Uncontrolled Components
- Prefer controlled components for form inputs — source of truth should be React state, not the DOM.

## 9. List Rendering & Keys
- Always use a stable, unique `key` from the data — never use array index as `key`.

```jsx
{users.map((user, index) => <UserCard key={index} user={user} />)} // Bad
{users.map(user => <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />)} // Good
```

## 10. Composition
- Prefer composition over deeply nested conditional rendering.
- Use `children` and render props for flexible, reusable components.

## 11. Performance
- Never pass inline objects or arrow functions as props — they create new references on every render.

```jsx
<UserCard style={{ margin: 0 }} onClick={() => handleSelect(user.id)} /> // Bad
const cardStyle = { margin: 0 };
const handleUserSelect = useCallback(() => handleSelect(user.id), [user.id]);
<UserCard style={cardStyle} onClick={handleUserSelect} /> // Good
```

- Memoize with `useMemo` and `useCallback` only when there is a measurable benefit — not by default.

## 12. Maintainability
- Remove unused props, state, effects, and handlers.
- Always define prop types — TypeScript interfaces/types for `.tsx`, PropTypes for `.jsx`.

## 13. Accessibility
- Use semantic HTML — `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation. Never use `<div>` or `<span>` as interactive elements.
- Always provide `alt` on images — use empty `alt=""` for decorative images.
- Add `aria-label` to icon-only buttons.
- Never remove focus `outline` without a visible replacement.
- Always associate form inputs with a `<label>` using `htmlFor` / `id`.

## Checklist
- Component has a single, clearly defined responsibility
- No large objects passed as props when only a subset is needed
- No prop drilling beyond two levels
- No direct state mutation — immutable update patterns used
- No state that duplicates or can be derived from existing state
- Functional state updates used when next state depends on previous
- Global state used only for genuinely shared cross-feature data
- No `useEffect` used to derive values that can be computed directly
- All effects have accurate dependency arrays and cleanup where needed
- No async function directly as `useEffect` callback
- No array index used as `key` in list rendering
- No business logic embedded directly in JSX
- No unnecessary `useMemo` or `useCallback` without a measurable reason
- Unused props, state, effects, and handlers removed
- Prop types defined — TypeScript types/interfaces for `.tsx`, PropTypes for `.jsx`
- Semantic HTML used — no `div`/`span` for interactive elements
- All images have `alt` text
- Icon-only buttons have `aria-label`
- Focus outline not removed without a visible replacement
- All form inputs have an associated `<label>`
